 in use for project detail pages.\n\nI'm thinking through how to handle the path parameter extraction—I could create dedicated handler methods that resolve the project directory first, then delegate to the core runs logic. The tricky part is that `resolveProjectDir` returns a JSON error response, but the HTML endpoint needs to handle errors differently.\n\nLooking at the existing code, `handleProjectDetail` already uses `resolveProjectDir` for its HTML handler despite the JSON error inconsistency, so I'll follow that same pattern rather than refactoring it now. My plan is to add two new routes: one for the HTML runs list at `/projects/{name}/runs` and another for the API at `/api/projects/{name}/runs`, each with their own handler that extracts the project from the path and reuses the existing logic.\n\nI'll update the templates and tests to point to the new URLs, and while the old query parameter approach can still work for backward compatibility, the new routes should be what the UI links to.\n\nNow I'm realizing the filter dropdown needs adjustment—it currently passes directory values to the navigation function, but with the new structure it should use project labels instead. I need to modify the dropdown to send labels and update the navigation logic to construct the correct `/projects/<label>/runs` path.\n\nFor the polling mechanism in the filtered view, I'll need to ensure the `currentProject` variable stores the label rather than the directory, and the API calls fetch from the appropriate label-based endpoint.\n\nThe template structure is getting more involved—I need to pass both the project directory and its label to the runs template so the dropdown navigation and polling can both reference the label correctly. The handler will resolve the label from the URL path and provide both values to the template for proper client-side functionality. to pass the project label to the template\n\nLet me think through the template data structure. I need to add the project label alongside the existing filter information so I can construct proper URLs in the templates.\n\nNow I'm mapping out the implementation plan. I'll need to add two new routes—one for the HTML view and one for the API endpoint—both handling project-specific run listings. Then I'll create the corresponding handler functions and update the existing runs list handler to include the project label in its template data. For the templates themselves, I need to update the dropdown to use labels as values, change the project filtering navigation to use the new URL structure, and update the project detail links accordingly.\n\nI'm also reconsidering the architecture here. Since both the all-projects view and the project-specific view will render the same template, the key is making sure the template knows which mode it's in. The template can use an empty project label to indicate the all-projects view, and a populated label for the project-specific view.\n\nFor the dropdown, I need to update the option values to use labels instead of directories, and adjust the comparison logic accordingly. When a user selects a project, they'll navigate to the project-specific runs page, and when they select all projects, they'll go back to the unfiltered view.\n\nUpdating the dropdown markup... , but I also need to handle the container count display. Let me keep `.Projects` as-is but change the value.\n\nOK, let me just write the code.\n\nFor `handleRunsList`, I'll stop handling the `?project=` query parameter. Actually, let me keep backward compat by redirecting from `/runs?project=<dir>` to `/projects/<label>/runs`. Or, simpler, I'll just update the handler to not pass the filter, and let the new route handle filtering. The old `?project=` URLs might still be bookmarked, so let me keep them working.\n\nActually, the simplest approach to maintain backward compatibility: Keep the existing `handleRunsList` with query param support, and add a new `handleProjectRunsList` for the path-based approach. Both render the same template. The template URLs/JS just use the new format.\n\nLet me proceed with this approach.\n\nFor `handleProjectRunsList`, I need to resolve the project label to its directory. I could reuse `resolveProjectDir`, but that returns JSON errors which won't work for an HTML page. Looking at how `handleProjectDetail` handles this, it uses the same function and returns JSON errors anyway, so I'll follow that pattern for consistency. I'm writing a handler that takes the label from the URL path, fetches all projects, builds a label-to-directory map, and finds the matching directory.\n\nWriting handler logic... Building the response template...\n\nI'm noticing there's a lot of duplication between this handler and `handleRunsList`, so I should refactor to consolidate the common logic. The key insight is that I can modify `handleRunsList` to accept the project from the URL path using `PathValue`, then fall back to the query parameter for backward compatibility, and register the same handler at both route patterns.\n\nHowever, there's a problem with this approach: `PathValue(\"name\")` only returns a value for the route pattern that actually has `{name}` in it, so for the `/runs` pattern without that parameter, it would always return an empty string. This is actually the correct behavior for Go's routing.\n\nI can register the same handler at both `/runs` and `/projects/{name}/runs` patterns. When the first pattern matches, `PathValue(\"name\")` returns empty, and when the second matches, it returns the project name. Go 1.22's pattern matching prioritizes more specific patterns, so `/projects/foo/runs` will correctly match the second pattern instead of conflicting with the existing `/projects/{name}` route for project details.\n\nLet me implement this approach for both the web and API handlers.\n\nUpdating the handlers to extract the project filter from the path parameter...\n\nI'm handling both the new URL structure with the project name in the path and the older query parameter approach for backward compatibility. When a project is specified, I'm resolving it to the actual directory and label, then fetching the appropriate runs from the store. If no project filter is provided, I'm just listing all runs.\n\nNow I need to figure out what data the template requires to work with both the dropdown and the table. The template needs the selected project label for marking the dropdown option, a mapping of all project labels for display, and the ability to construct the new-style URLs. I'm going to implement this by using labels as the dropdown values and comparing against the selected project label to determine which option should be marked as selected.\n\nI should also apply the same approach to `handleAPIRuns` and think through whether the dropdown still needs the directory information—it doesn't, since navigation is now label-based, though the backend still needs it for filtering. Let me refactor the handler to pass the project label to the template instead.\n\nNow I'm realizing that when the polling JavaScript updates the table on a project-scoped page, it needs to use the project-scoped API endpoint instead of the global one, constructing the URL with the label as the project identifier. I have a clear implementation plan: add the new routes to handler.go, update the handlers to work with labels, and adjust the polling logic to use the scoped endpoints.\n\nFor the frontend changes, I need to update the dropdown to use labels, modify the filtering to navigate to the label-based URL, and ensure the polling uses the correct scoped API. I'll also need to update the project links across the templates and add tests to verify the new routing works while potentially maintaining backward compatibility with the query parameter approach.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":37455,"cache_read_input_tokens":15819,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_